org.cloudgraph.recognizer

Class GraphRecognizerSyntaxTreeAssembler

  • java.lang.Object
    • DefaultQueryVisitor
      • org.cloudgraph.query.expr.ExpresionVisitorSupport
        • org.cloudgraph.query.expr.DefaultBinaryExprTreeAssembler
          • org.cloudgraph.recognizer.GraphRecognizerSyntaxTreeAssembler
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    ExprAssembler

    public class GraphRecognizerSyntaxTreeAssembler
extends DefaultBinaryExprTreeAssembler
    A binary expression tree assembler which constructs an operator precedence map, then visits (traverses) the given predicate expression syntax tree depth-first using an adapted shunting-yard algorithm and assembles a resulting binary tree structure with expression nodes specific for detecting i.e. recognizing a data graph. In typical usage scenarios, a single expression tree is assembled once, and then used to evaluate any number of data graphs.

    The adapted shunting-yard algorithm in general uses a stack of operators and operands, and as new binary tree nodes are detected and created they are pushed onto the operand stack based on operator precedence. The resulting binary expression tree reflects the syntax of the underlying query expression including the precedence of its operators.

    Since:
    0.5.3
    Author:
    Scott Cinnamond
